Read the full results of the Suffolk/Globe poll of New Hampshire voters here:

The poll suggested little about this race is set in stone: Twenty-one percent of likely N.H. voters were undecided. When those who chose a candidate were pressed, more than half said they might change their minds before the N.H. primary.

In fact, about half of likely Democratic primary voters in New Hampshire say they won’t consider voting for Deval Patrick because he waited too long to jump into the crowded presidential field, according to the poll.
All other candidates, including former Massachusetts governor Deval Patrick, who jumped in the race this month, were in single digits. http://bos.gl/63MAVmy

The survey found Bernie Sanders, who won the N.H. primary in 2016, leading the field there with 16 percent, including those who lean toward the candidate. Elizabeth Warren had 14 percent, Pete Buttigieg had 13 percent, and Joe Biden had 12 percent. http://bos.gl/lCEOKqA

Governor Baker’s administration has made significant and long overdue investments in the #MBTA and commuter rail. At $292 per resident, Massachusetts spent more per capita on transit in 2017 than any other state. http://bos.gl/3hxWf4N

The #MBTA has more derailments than almost any other metro transit system, and costs more, too. The subway system has suffered about 40 derailments in the last five years, more than almost any other system in the country. http://bos.gl/oITAjEd

“The unknown, which is the great fear, becomes the familiar,” said Bob Curry, who runs a Hazleton community center. “And when it’s the familiar, your biases start to dissipate.”
But Soto said Hazleton is becoming more open, even among older residents. “We are past that,” she said of the city’s earlier controversy. “We can give the whole nation a lesson if they want.”

It’s not without tension: A reporter had an older white woman at a church fair tell her that “the Latino community doesn’t want to assimilate” the way her family did. . . while Nicarol Soto, the first Latina to win a Democratic primary for Hazleton City Council, walked by.
Like the Rodriguezes, who came to Hazleton for warehouse jobs and now own a yellow brick duplex that feels like a castle. “We are seeing our kids flourish here,” said Penelope Rodriguez said.
This story explores the lives of those who have been in Hazleton forever, and those who moved in more recently, many of whom are seeking -- and finding -- a middle class life for their families.

Amilcar Arroyo, publisher of the Spanish language paper, keeps a running list of all the contributions of the Latino community on a whiteboard in his office: grocery stores, restaurants, bars, discotheques, furniture stores, and more. “This is what we have brought to Hazleton.”

“What’s been happening in the US happened in Hazleton in 2006.” That’s when the City Council voted to make English its official language. Since then, the former mayor left for a stint in Congress and a Senate loss, and the Latino population kept surging.

In the latest in our series about crucial 2020 states, we went to Hazleton, Pa., a formerly dying city that now has a majority Latino population. Its story could teach the rest of the US a thing or two.
